  <!-- WORKED EXAMPLE 6 -->
  <div class="example-card">
    <div class="example-header">
      <span class="eg-tag">Worked Example 6.1</span>
      <h4>Rebar Selection for a Required Tensile Force</h4>
    </div>
    <p class="eg-problem"><strong>Problem:</strong> A beam tensile force at midspan requires As ≥ 2.15 in². Using Grade 60 steel, select a suitable bar arrangement. Check that bars fit within a 12-in wide beam with adequate spacing.</p>
    <div class="eg-steps">
      <div class="eg-step"><span class="step-num">1</span><div><strong>Required As = 2.15 in².</strong> Try 3 × #8: As = 3 × 0.79 = 2.37 in² ≥ 2.15 ✓ (10% over — acceptable)</div></div>
      <div class="eg-step"><span class="step-num">2</span><div><strong>Alternate: 4 × #7:</strong> As = 4 × 0.60 = 2.40 in² ✓. More bars, smaller diameter.</div></div>
      <div class="eg-step"><span class="step-num">3</span><div><strong>Spacing check for 3 × #8 in 12-in beam:</strong>
        Cover = 1.5 in, stirrup = 0.375 in, bar dia = 1.0 in.
        Available width = 12 − 2(1.5) − 2(0.375) − 3(1.0) = 12 − 3 − 0.75 − 3 = 5.25 in for 2 gaps → spacing = 5.25/2 = 2.63 in ≥ 1.5 × 1.0 = 1.5 in ✓
      </div></div>
      <div class="eg-step"><span class="step-num">4</span><div><strong>Tensile force provided:</strong> \( T = A_s \cdot f_y = 2.37 \times 60 = 142.2 \text&#123; kips&#125; \)</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="eg-answer">
      <strong>Answer:</strong> Use 3 × #8 bars (As = 2.37 in²). Spacing = 2.63 in > minimum. T = 142 kips available.
    </div>
  </div>

